We had to cancel the last three dishes that didn't come...this was after 1.5 hours after we ordered.  The food wasn't even good this time around either.  The dishes that were not server were the combo fried rice, egg Foo young, and a noodle dish...all easy dishes.  We ended up paying over $120 for a large egg drop soup, two appetizers, and three dishes.  I hate to say it, but this is our last time coming here.

Visited this place after it was highly recommended by two people whose opinions I value.  Overall, it was a disappointing experience.  The food and prices were adequate, but no different or better than a number of other places in China Town or scattered across the city.  What they're desperately lacking is any type of organization.  We arrived at about 6:30 on a Saturday evening with a party of 7.  The restaurant was about 2/3's full.  So, it was busy, but not overwhelmed.  There seemed to be plenty of servers.  The problem was with the kitchen, not the wait staff.  We ordered two appetizers for the table, which came out about 10 minutes apart.  One of the children ordered an appetizer as his meal, and that came out in another 10 minutes.  Then the remaining six people were served their dishes one at time, about 5-10 minutes apart.  It was a good half hour, 45 minutes between the time the first person and the last person were served.  Two hours for an average dinner.  Highly doubtful any of us will ever be back, especially considering all of the other excellent restaurants in the area.

When my husband went up to pay the check the lady at the front insisted on him tipping. My husband tells her no im not tipping. She still acts like she doesnt understand and keeps pointing at the tip line. She wouldn't let him leave without reminding him that he didn't tip. At that point i make sure i tell her why we are not tipping reminding her that tips are earned and not just given. She then says she will let the manager know. I don't understand how you can push for tips with no shame when your waitresses clearly don't do anything. Service here is terrible.

I can't remember the last time I was here. I came here with my family after a funeral. We ordered the typical banquet meal. Some standouts were the roasted pork (did not like the pickled vegetables underneath) and the beef and gai lan. But I did not like the tilapia (oil tasted old/smoky, which imparted a weird aftertaste), sweet and sour pork (not very crispy, just felt like it was slathered in sauce). I thought it was interesting to be served a sweet ginger dessert soup with noodles rather than balls or tapioca.  Additionally, when you enter the restaurant, it's like you're transported back to the 80s/90s. However, service was prompt although we were pretty much the only customers in the entire restaurant.

I really only come to Evergreen for family feasts.  If you've never had an Asian family style dinner, it's the menu written completely in Chinese and value priced because you can't read it.  The family style "prix fixe" usually consists of 8 to 10 courses and a number of the dishes have some old world meaning.  It's a great progression of food and covers all of the meat and vegetable groups.  Evergreen is an old school style restaurant that serves the old school people of Chinatown.  This isn't a bad thing and I hope that they continue to consistently serve the traditional family dinners that I'm accustomed to for celebrations big and small.  Evergreen is a good place with good food and decent service.
